# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bifidobacterium
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] An **acetate** is a salt formed by the combination of acetic acid with a base (e.g. alkaline, earthy, metallic, nonmetallic, or radical base).
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] "Acetate" also describes the conjugate base or ion (specifically, the negatively charged ion called an anion) typically found in aqueous solution and written with the chemical formula C 2H 3O− 2.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] The neutral molecules formed by the combination of the acetate ion and a *positive* ion (called a cation) are also commonly called "acetates" (hence, *acetate of lead*, *acetate of aluminium*, etc.).
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] The simplest of these is hydrogen acetate (called acetic acid) with corresponding salts, esters, and the polyatomic anion CH 3CO− 2, or CH 3COO− .
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Most of the approximately 5 million tonnes of acetic acid produced annually in industry are used in the production of acetates, which usually take the form of polymers.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] In nature, acetate is the most common building block for biosynthesis.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] When part of a salt, the formula of the acetate ion is written as CH 3CO− 2, C 2H 3O− 2, or CH 3COO− .
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Chemists often represent acetate as OAc− or, less commonly, AcO−.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Thus, HOAc is the symbol for acetic acid, NaOAc for sodium acetate, and EtOAc for ethyl acetate (as Ac is common symbol for acetyl group CH3CO).
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] The pseudoelement symbol "Ac" is also sometimes encountered in chemical formulas as indicating the entire acetate ion (CH 3CO− 2).
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] It is not to be confused with the symbol of actinium, the first element of the actinide series; context guides disambiguation.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] For example, the formula for sodium acetate might be abbreviated as "NaOAc", rather than "NaC2H3O2".
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Care should also be taken to avoid confusion with peracetic acid when using the OAc abbreviation; for clarity and to avoid errors when translated, HOAc should be avoided in literature mentioning both compounds.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Although its systematic name is *ethanoate* (/ɪˈθænoʊ.eɪt/), the common *acetate* remains the preferred IUPAC name.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] The acetate anion, [CH3COO]−,(or [C2H3O2]−) is one of the carboxylate family.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] It is the conjugate base of acetic acid.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Many acetate salts are ionic, indicated by their tendency to dissolve well in water.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Transition metals can be complexed by acetate.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Examples of acetate complexes include chromium(II) acetate and many other transition metal carboxylate complexes.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Commercially important acetate salts are aluminium acetate, used in dyeing, ammonium acetate, a precursor to acetamide, and potassium acetate, used as a diuretic.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] All three salts are colourless and highly soluble in water.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Acetate esters have the general formula CH3CO2R, where R is an organyl group.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] The esters are the dominant forms of acetate in the marketplace.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Unlike the acetate salts, acetate esters are often liquids, lipophilic, and sometimes volatile.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] They are popular because they have inoffensive, often sweet odors, they are inexpensive, and they are usually of low toxicity.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Almost half of acetic acid production is consumed in the production of vinyl acetate, precursor to polyvinyl alcohol, which is a component of many paints.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] The second largest use of acetic acid is consumed in the production of cellulose acetate.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] In fact, "acetate" is jargon for cellulose acetate, which is used in the production of fibres or diverse products, e.g. the acetate discs used in audio record production.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Cellulose acetate can be found in many household products.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Many industrial solvents are acetates, including methyl acetate, ethyl acetate, isopropyl acetate, and ethylhexyl acetate.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Butyl acetate is a fragrance used in food products.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] It is mainly utilized by organisms in the form of acetyl coenzyme A.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Intraperitoneal injection of sodium acetate (20 or 60 mg per kg body mass) was found to induce headache in sensitized rats, and it has been proposed that acetate resulting from oxidation of ethanol is a major factor in causing hangovers.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Increased serum acetate levels lead to accumulation of adenosine in many tissues including the brain, and administration of the adenosine receptor antagonist caffeine to rats after ethanol was found to decrease nociceptive behavior.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Acetate has known immunomodulatory properties and can affect the innate immune response to pathogenic bacteria such as the respiratory pathogen *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Pyruvate is converted into acetyl-coenzyme A (acetyl-CoA) by the enzyme pyruvate dehydrogenase.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] This acetyl-CoA is then converted into acetate in *E. coli*, whilst producing ATP by substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] Acetate formation requires two enzymes: phosphate acetyltransferase and acetate kinase.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] This disproportionation reaction is catalysed by methanogen archaea in their fermentative metabolism.
[src:bifidobacterium/acetate] One electron is transferred from the carbonyl function (e− donor) of the carboxylic group to the methyl group (e− acceptor) of acetic acid to respectively produce CO2 and methane gas.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidimicrobiia] The ***Acidimicrobiia*** are a class of Actinomycetota, in which three families, eight genera, and nine species have been described, *Acidimicrobium ferrooxidans* is the type species of the order.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidimicrobiia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriia] The "**Acidobacteriia**" is a class of Acidobacteriota.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriia] Numbered orders do not yet have any cultured representatives.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Acidulidesulfobacteriota are ecologically significant in biogeochemical cycling, especially with respect to sulfur and iron.
[src:bifidobacterium/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Their genomes show evidence of interaction with viruses, which can influence host metabolic functions including folate biosynthesis and sulfur pathways.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Before the 1960s, *Bifidobacterium* species were collectively referred to as *Lactobacillus bifidus*.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Underlying most of the beneficial effects of *Bifidobacterium* are improved immune system function and reduction in inflammation.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Notably, *Bifidobacterium* increases regulatory T cells and improves the intestinal barrier.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] *Bifidobacterium* produces essential metabolites for use by other key bacteria.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] *Bifidobacterium* carbohydrate fermentation produces acetate and butyrate, which can protect against various diseases.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] In 1899, Henri Tissier, a French pediatrician at the Pasteur Institute in Paris, isolated a bacterium characterised by a Y-shaped morphology ("bifid") in the intestinal microbiota of breast-fed infants and named it "bifidus".
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] In 1907, Élie Metchnikoff, deputy director at the Pasteur Institute, propounded the theory that lactic acid bacteria are beneficial to human health.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Metchnikoff observed that the longevity of Bulgarians was the result of their consumption of fermented milk products.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Metchnikoff also suggested that "oral administration of cultures of fermentative bacteria would implant the beneficial bacteria in the intestinal tract".
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] The genus *Bifidobacterium* possesses a unique fructose-6-phosphate phosphoketolase pathway employed to ferment carbohydrates.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Much metabolic research on bifidobacteria has focused on oligosaccharide metabolism, as these carbohydrates are available in their otherwise nutrient-limited habitats.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Infant-associated bifidobacterial phylotypes appear to have evolved the ability to ferment milk oligosaccharides, whereas adult-associated species use plant oligosaccharides, consistent with what they encounter in their respective environments.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] As breast-fed infants often harbor bifidobacteria-dominated gut consortia, numerous applications attempt to mimic the bifidogenic properties of milk oligosaccharides.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] These are broadly classified as plant-derived fructooligosaccharides or dairy-derived galactooligosaccharides, which are differentially metabolized and distinct from milk oligosaccharide catabolism.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] The sensitivity of members of the genus *Bifidobacterium* to O2 generally limits probiotic activity to anaerobic habitats.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Recent research has reported that some *Bifidobacterium* strains exhibit various types of oxic growth.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Low concentrations of O2 and CO2 can have a stimulatory effect on the growth of these *Bifidobacterium* strains.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Based on the growth profiles under different O2 concentrations, the *Bifidobacterium* species were classified into four classes: O2-hypersensitive, O2-sensitive, O2-tolerant, and microaerophilic.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] The primary factor responsible for aerobic growth inhibition is proposed to be the production of hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) in the growth medium.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] A H2O2-forming NADH oxidase was purified from O2-sensitive *Bifidobacterium bifidum* and was identified as a *b*-type dihydroorotate dehydrogenase.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] The kinetic parameters suggested that the enzyme could be involved in H2O2 production in highly aerated environments.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Members of the genus *Bifidobacterium* have genome sizes ranging from 1.73 (*Bifidobacterium indicum*) to 3.25 Mb (*Bifidobacterium biavatii*), corresponding to 1,352 and 2,557 predicted protein-encoding open reading frames, respectively.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Functional classification of *Bifidobacterium* genes, including the pan-genome of this genus, revealed that 13.7% of the identified bifidobacterial genes encode enzymes involved in carbohydrate metabolism.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Adding *Bifidobacterium* as a probiotic to conventional treatment of ulcerative colitis has been shown to be associated with improved rates of remission and improved maintenance of remission.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Some *Bifidobacterium* strains are considered as important probiotics and used in the food industry.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Bifidobacteria improve the gut mucosal barrier and lower levels of lipopolysaccharide in the intestine.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Bifidobacteria may also improve abdominal pain in patients with irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) though studies to date have been inconclusive.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Naturally occurring *Bifidobacterium* spp. may discourage the growth of Gram-negative pathogens in infants.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] A mother's milk contains high concentrations of lactose and lower quantities of phosphate (pH buffer).
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Therefore, when mother's milk is fermented by lactic acid bacteria (including bifidobacteria) in the infant's gastrointestinal tract, the pH may be reduced, making it more difficult for Gram-negative bacteria to grow.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] The human infant gut is relatively sterile up until birth, where it takes up bacteria from its surrounding environment and its mother.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] The microbiota that makes up the infant gut differs from the adult gut.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] An infant reaches the adult stage of their microbiome at around three years of age, when their microbiome diversity increases, stabilizes, and the infant switches over to solid foods.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Breast-fed infants are colonized earlier by *Bifidobacterium* when compared to babies that are primarily formula-fed.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] *Bifidobacterium* is the most common bacteria in the infant gut microbiome.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] There is more variability in genotypes over time in infants, making them less stable compared to the adult *Bifidobacterium*.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Infants and children under three years old show low diversity in microbiome bacteria, but more diversity between individuals when compared to adults.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Reduction of *Bifidobacterium* and increase in diversity of the infant gut microbiome occurs with less breast-milk intake and increase of solid food intake.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Mammalian milk all contain oligosaccharides showing natural selection.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Human milk oligosaccharides are not digested by enzymes and remain whole through the digestive tract before being broken down in the colon by microbiota.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] *Bifidobacterium* species genomes of *B. longum, B. bifidum, B. breve* contain genes that can hydrolyze some of the human milk oligosaccharides and these are found in higher numbers in infants that are breast-fed.
[src:bifidobacterium/bifidobacterium] Glycans that are produced by the humans are converted into food and energy for the *B. bifidum.* showing an example of coevolution.
